==Notes==
{{note label|Location|A|A}}A Worts Travelling Bachelorship (now known as a Worts Travelling Scholars Fund) is the result of a bequest by Wiliam Worts, who died in 1709.<ref name=h68/>  It makes grants "for the promotion or encouragement of investigations in countries outside Great Britain respecting the religion, learning, law, politics, customs, manner and rarities, natural or artificial, of those countries, or for purposes of geographical discovery or of antiquarian or scientific research in such countries".<ref>{{Citation |title= Statutes and Ordinances of the University of Cambridge |chapter= XII: Trust Emoluments |publisher= [[University of Cambridge]] |url= http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/univ/so/2011/chapter12-section2.html#heading2-593 |accessdate =23&nbsp;February 2012}}</ref><br>
{{note label|Location|B|B}}A further Commissioners' church was later designed in conjunction with Paley, [[St Saviour's Church, Ringley|St&nbsp;Saviour, Ringley]] (1850<U+2013>54).<ref>{{Harvnb|Port|2006|p=335.}}</ref><br/>
{{note label|Location|C|C}}Holy Trinity is now [[redundant church|redundant]] and is in the care of the [[Churches Conservation Trust]], the only one of Sharpe's churches to be so preserved.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hughes|2010|p=161.}}</ref><br/>
{{note label|Location|D|D}}Unfortunately the spire was not as durable as the rest of the church.  By 1936 it had become unsafe, and was dismantled.  In 1966 the lantern and bell-tower were also demolished.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hughes|2010|p=257.}}</ref><br>
{{note label|Location|E|E}}The tower was not completed until 1850.  It was built from terracotta of inferior quality, and was later found to be unsafe, having to be rebuilt in 1912.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hughes|2010|p=270.}}</ref><br/>
{{note label|Location|F|F}}The two older boys were educated at [[Rossall School]], and Alfred at [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College|Haileybury College]].  Francis became the proprietor of the Phoenix Foundry, while Edmund (junior) joined the textile-coating firm of Storey Brothers, Lancaster, and later became [[Lord of the Manor]] of [[Halton-with-Aughton|Halton]].  [[Alfred Sharpe|Alfred]] had a career as a big-game hunter in Central Africa, then as a colonial civil servant, being knighted in 1897, and later becoming the first Governor of [[Nyasaland]] (now [[Malawi]]).  The girls did not marry, living together in [[Ambleside]] and later moving back to Lancaster.<ref name=h533/><br/>
{{note label|Location|G|G}}An example of this is given in {{Citation |last= Bumpus |first= T. Francis |year= c. 1920(?) |title= A Guide to Gothic Architecture |publication-place = London |publisher= T. Werner Laurie |page=76}}, which states "Mr Sharpe (d. 1877) was one of the earliest, ablest and most zealous pioneers of the English Gothic revival".<ref>Quoted by {{Harvnb|Hughes|2010|p=433.}}</ref>

